# Code review

## What to check (in order)

1. Right thing? Validate the intended goal/outcome first — does the change build
   what was actually asked for?
2. Thing right? Understand the design and trade-offs; challenge assumptions and rationale.
3. Concrete defects. Surface bugs, regressions, risks, and missing tests.
4. Maintainability. Prefer generalized, reusable approaches over one-offs; will this
   age well, or is it a brittle special case?
5. Simplicity & conciseness. Actively look for ways to simplify, tighten, and make
   the change more concise — ideally it removes more lines than it adds (see
   `my-engineering-principles`).
6. Principles. Evaluate the change against `my-engineering-principles` — less-is-more,
   early-exit guards, fail loud, no dead code, self-documenting names, systems thinking,
   idiomatic & declarative design, and the SOLID/YAGNI ladder.
7. Conventions. Adherence to codebase/community conventions and principles —
   follow the rules until you know when to break them. Flag task, ticket, PR,
   review-discussion, or session-specific narrative leaking into source comments or
   state-describing documentation instead of describing the code/system as it stands
   (see `my-commenting`, `my-writing`) — not a flag against legitimate PR/commit/Jira/
   incident rationale, which belongs in `my-audit-trail`'s artifacts.

## Output

- Findings first, in severity order, each with a `file:line` reference.
- Summary secondary.
- If there are no findings, say so explicitly — and still note residual risks or
  testing gaps.
